Statistical machine learning, Lab 7

Local regression and Generalized Additive Models

R packages we use in the lab

We are going to use tidymodels framework and mgcv package for GAM model fitting. An alternative implementation of GAM models is in the gam package, but since mgcv is considered more universal and can be used in tidymodels framework, we are not going to use the modeling command from gam.

Datasets of the lab

We are going to use Auto dataset from ISLR package.

Local regression

Local regression computes a predicted value at a given predictor value \(x\) by choosing a certain fraction of observations from training data with predictor values closest to \(x\) and fitting a low order polynomial regression model to those observations. The smoothness of the resulting predictor function is controlled by the fraction of points used. The command for fitting local regression curve is loess(), which is contained in the stats package. The most important parameters of the command are

  • formula, which determines the response variable and up to 4 predictors
  • data - data frame with training set information
  • span - should be between 0 and 1 (default is 0.75), describes the proportion of observations used around gived \(x\) value
  • degree - degree of polynomials used. Default is 2, possible values are 0,1,2.
  • control=loess.control(surface="direct") - forces actual local regression to be used. By default a certain number of local regression models are fitted and for new observations those models are used

Exercise 1

Fit a local regression curve to log(mpg) as a function of horsepower by using quadratic regression and span=0.1, 0.5, 0.8

y=log(ISLR::Auto$mpg)
x=ISLR::Auto$horsepower
newx=seq(min(x),max(x),length.out=201)
df1=data.frame(x=x,y=y)
lr_model1=loess(y~x,data=df1,span=0.8,control = loess.control(surface="direct"))
df2=data.frame(x=newx,.fitted=predict(lr_model1,data.frame(x=newx)))
plot=ggplot(df1,aes(x=x))+geom_point(aes(y=y))+geom_line(data=df2,aes(x=x,y=.fitted,color="span=0.8"),lwd=1.2)
lr_model2=loess(y~x,data=df1,span=0.5,control = loess.control(surface="direct"))
df2=data.frame(x=newx,.fitted=predict(lr_model2,data.frame(x=newx)))
plot=plot+geom_line(data=df2,aes(x=x,y=.fitted,color="span=0.5"),lwd=1.2)
lr_model3=loess(y~x,data=df1,span=0.1,control = loess.control(surface="direct"))
df2=data.frame(x=newx,.fitted=predict(lr_model3,data.frame(x=newx)))
plot=plot+geom_line(data=df2,aes(x=x,y=.fitted,color="span=0.1"),lwd=1.2)
plot

Since local regression is generally very time consuming when computing predictions (for each data point a new model has to be fitted), it is not very widely used as a component of high dimensional models. But if you want to try out GAM models with smooth terms computed by local regression, then it is possible to use gam() function from the package gam, which unfortunately can not be used with tidymodels framework. Therefore we do not consider it in this course.

Fitting a generalized linear model with many predictors

Information about fitting GAM models with tidymodels framework:

  • the GAM model is specified with gen_additive_mod() command. This command has parameters mode (classification or regression), engine (currently only mgcv), select_features (TRUE of FALSE, should automatic feature selection be performed with additional penalty terms) and adjust_deg_free (numeric, values larger than 1 increase smoothness of the result).
  • one-variable smoothing terms can be indicated with a term s(variable) in the model formula
  • the model can be fitted by several approaches:
    • model specification with fit command of the form: model_spec |> fit(formula,data)
    • by using workflows with formula indicated when model is added: the term add_model() in the workflow definition should be of the form add_model(model_spec,formula=formula_with_smoothing_terms)

Let us fit some GAM models for predicting log(mpg) by using several variables from the Auto data set.

Exercise 2

Use stats::step() function to find the best linear regression model by starting from the model which uses all variables except name. Note that origin should be used as a factor variable. Check for bias with respect to all continuous variables used in the fit. Which ones may require nonlinear modelling?

Solution Fit a model and produce graphs:

Auto_mod=ISLR::Auto|> mutate(logmpg=log(mpg),origin=factor(origin,levels=1:3))|>select(-mpg)
m3=stats::step(lm(logmpg ~ cylinders + displacement + horsepower + 
    weight + origin + year+acceleration, data = Auto_mod))

As we see, there are reasons to believe that it may be necessary to add nonlinear effects with respect to all continuous variables except, possibly, the variable cylinders. Although cylinders is used as continuous variable in the model, it has a small number of different values, some of which have a very small number of observations. It may be a good idea to add nonlinearities sequentially, since (especially in the case of strongly correlated variables like horsepower and weight) it may happen that after modelling nonlinearity with respect to some variables nonlinear effects with respect to some other variable disappear.

Exercise 3

Fit a generalized additive model to the data by adding natural spline with 3 degrees of freedom to year variable and smoothing splines to displacement and weight terms (keeping other therms from the best model of the previous exercise). Compare by 5-fold cross-validation the results obtained with similar model where three-dimensional smoothing term in the form of tensor products (indicated with term te()) is added instead of individual smoothing and spline terms. Which model is better?

Solution

m4=gen_additive_mod(mode="regression")|>fit(logmpg ~ cylinders + s(displacement) + horsepower + s(weight) + origin + 
    splines::ns(year,df=3),data=Auto_mod)
#add predictions to data and compute correct residuals
df4=augment(m4, new_data=Auto_mod)
ggplot(df4,aes(x=year))+geom_point(aes(y=.resid))+geom_smooth(aes(y=.resid))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(df4,aes(x=displacement))+geom_point(aes(y=.resid))+geom_smooth(aes(y=.resid))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(df4,aes(x=weight))+geom_point(aes(y=.resid))+geom_smooth(aes(y=.resid))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(df4,aes(x=horsepower))+geom_point(aes(y=.resid))+geom_smooth(aes(y=.resid))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(df4,aes(x=acceleration))+geom_point(aes(y=.resid))+geom_smooth(aes(y=.resid))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula = 'y ~ x'

We see that nonlinear effects with respect to time, displacement and weight have been modeled quite well. Additionally, nonlinear effects with respect to horsepower and acceleration have also disappeared. We can see the shape and relative effect of the smooth terms with command plot(model,pages=1) where model is the result of mgcv::gam(). If we used tidymodels framework for fitting with model_spec|>fit() command, then the model can be obtained by fitted_model$fit. If we want to get predictions for each term in the model, it is possible to use command predict(fitted_model,new_data=something,type="raw",opts=list(type="terms")).

plot(m4$fit,pages=1)

tmp=data.frame(predict(m4,new_data = ISLR::Auto,type="raw",opts = list(type="terms")))
tibble(tmp)
m5=gen_additive_mod(mode="regression")|>fit(logmpg ~ cylinders  + horsepower + te(weight,displacement,year) + origin ,data=Auto_mod)
#compare models by separate crossvalidation
set.seed(20241017)
cv=vfold_cv(Auto_mod,v=5)
wf4 = workflow()|>add_recipe(recipe(logmpg~.,data=Auto_mod))|>add_model(gen_additive_mod(mode="regression"),formula=logmpg ~  cylinders + s(displacement) + horsepower + s(weight) + origin + 
    splines::ns(year,df=3))
res4=fit_resamples(wf4,cv,metrics = metric_set(rmse))
collect_metrics(res4)
wf5 = workflow()|>add_recipe(recipe(logmpg~.,data=Auto_mod))|>add_model(gen_additive_mod(mode="regression"),formula=logmpg ~ cylinders  + horsepower + te(weight,displacement,year) + origin)
res5=fit_resamples(wf5,cv,metrics = metric_set(rmse))
collect_metrics(res5)
#separate terms gave better average performance in the case of crossvalidation.

Exercise 4

Instead of using tensor product splines, it is possible to fit multivariate non-linear smoothing terms with thin plate splines by including multiple variables in a single s() command and leaving the parameter bs to it’s default value (which is “tp”, thin plate splines). When using multivariate thin plate splines, the variables should be on a similar scale, so normalization is recommended. Compute cross-validation results of fitting similar model as previously with te() term without normalization and compare the results to the case, when the variables year,weigth and displacement are normalised.

Solution

m6=gen_additive_mod(mode="regression")|>fit(logmpg ~ cylinders  + horsepower + s(weight,displacement,year) + origin ,Auto_mod)
wf6a=workflow()|>add_recipe(recipe(logmpg~.,data=Auto_mod))|>add_model(gen_additive_mod(mode="regression"),formula=logmpg ~ cylinders  + horsepower + s(weight,displacement,year) + origin)
res6a=fit_resamples(wf6a,cv,metrics = metric_set(rmse))
collect_metrics(res6a)
#separate terms gave better average performance in the case of crossvalidation.
wf6b=workflow()|>add_recipe(recipe(logmpg~.,data=Auto_mod)|>step_normalize(weight,displacement,year))|>add_model(gen_additive_mod(mode="regression"),formula=logmpg ~ cylinders  + horsepower + s(weight,displacement,year) + origin)
res6b=fit_resamples(wf6b,cv,metrics = metric_set(rmse))
collect_metrics(res6b)
